metadata.name: Ornithic #230
metadata.description:
Pure p5.js code. No svg, no image, no other materials. Creating code arts with polar coordinate system and algorithms are my passion. This generative art contains a lot of features that may be rare than common.  

• 30 color palettes // 2 of them have 3 different colors
• 4 grass structures // With the same algorithm 
• 16 flower types //  Count, leaf number and size
• 6 color functions // Different colorizations with b&w 

Also, the outputs of the project are very high resolution to print or something like that.
April / 2022
Rhaegar

metadata.name: Perpetual Oscillations  #17
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Ray Drops #84
metadata.description:
Ray Drops plays with the idea of rays that are projected out from a random center point which oscillate at variable frequencies. At each inflection point it has a chance of being intersected by a ring. The inflection points vary in how closely they are spaced and can cluster around the center point or fan all the way out to the edges. 

When run this generative creates a 12 layer SVG vector that is designed to be run on a laser cutter in order to build an in real life woodcut. Each layer is a single contiguous piece with no floating elements so when cut out of wood you end up with 12 layers that can be secured with 10 Chicago screws.  

Learn more and get physical editions: https://alleditions.art/p/ray-drops

Shift P - exports a PNG
Shift S - exports SVG
Shift E - explodes the layers

The 5 rarest mints (once the series is minted out) will receive a free signed physical which can be claimed by an owner of the NFT at anytime. It can be left attached and claimed by any future owner. 

I will also be giving away 5 free signed physicals randomly to people who tweet a picture of their edition and tag @shawnkemp

metadata.name: Mooving Squigly #174
metadata.description:
A mooving squigly generator inspirated by "Chromie Squiggle by snowfro"
@ArtOnBlockchain on twitter
Made using p5.js

This project aim to be your unique mooving web3 signature

The features define the visual of your squigly
DIFFERENT FEATURES :

    Background Color: #7AA5A6, #FBB900, #FCBF49, #FFFFFF, #F5F3EC, #1F1F1F, #F9EBDC, #F0C328, #8AC1CC
    Squigly Color Theme: flash, chromatic, cloud, kaki, darkred
    Stroke: none, max 10
    Squigly Number: 1, 2, 3
    Special Color Mode: true, false
    Squigly Size: medium, small, large, extra large
    Speed: max 5
    Style: classic, expansion, distortion, blur, gray

The colours and positions are calculated using deterministic perlin noise
Press S to save the squigly
Reload the page to see your squigly moove again

Made with <3 by 0xtedy.tez / @0xtedy
All the code is opensource !
MIT License
